Business Analytics with Superstore Data

Bernard Ade

Superstore dataset comes with downloads of Tableau. Tableau is an extremely fast and convenient tool for conducting data analysis. However, working with data in R is powerful, free, expressive and it helps to build intuition whereas in Tableau it all seems like magic. Lets dive in!

Import Library

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(gridExtra)

Import Data

superstore = read_csv("superstore.csv")

Data Wrangling

names(superstore) = tolower(gsub(" ", "_", names(superstore))) 
superstore$order_date = as.Date(superstore$order_date, "%m/%d/%y")
superstore$ship_date = as.Date(superstore$ship_date, "%m/%d/%y")
superstore$day_of_week = wday(superstore$order_date, label = TRUE)
superstore$month = month(superstore$order_date, label = TRUE)
superstore$profit_loss = ifelse(superstore$profit > 0, "profit", "loss")
superstore$discounted = ifelse(superstore$discount == 0, "no_discount", "discount")
superstore$profit_ratio = superstore$profit/superstore$sales * 100

Inspect Dataset

superstore

Sales and Profit & Loss Analysis

superstore %>%
ggplot(aes(x = region, fill = profit_loss)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8) +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("profit"="#1F77B4", "loss"="#B71C1C")) +
    theme(legend.position = "right") +
    labs(title = "Count of Profit & Loss by Region", x = "", fill = "")

superstore %>%
ggplot(aes(x = state, fill = profit_loss)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8) +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("profit"="#1F77B4", "loss"="#B71C1C")) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1)) +
    theme(legend.position = "right") +
    labs(title = "Count of Profit & Loss by State", x = "", fill = "")

superstore %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = order_date, color = profit_loss)) +
    geom_freqpoly(bins = 100, size = .7, alpha = 0.8) +
    facet_grid(profit_loss ~ ., scales = "free") +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("profit"="#1F77B4", "loss"="#B71C1C"))  +
    guides(color = FALSE)+
  labs(title = "Count of Profit & Loss by Date", x = "", fill = "")

superstore %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = order_date, y = ..density.., color = profit_loss)) +
    geom_freqpoly(size = .7, alpha = 0.8, bins = 100) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("profit"="#1F77B4", "loss"="#B71C1C")) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title = "Density of Profit & Loss by Date", x = "", color = "")

superstore %>%
  mutate(day = format(order_date, "%d")) %>%
  group_by(month, day) %>%
  summarise(sum_sales = sum(sales)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = day, fill = sum_sales)) +
    geom_tile(alpha = 0.8, color = "white") +
    scale_fill_gradientn(colours = c("#1F77B4" ,"#B71C1C")) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "right") +
    labs(title = "Sales per Month and Day", x = "Month", y = "Day of the Month", fill = "Sales")

superstore %>%
ggplot(aes(x=sales, y=profit, color = profit_loss)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.8) + 
    scale_color_brewer(type='seq') +
    theme_minimal() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
    labs(title = "Sales & Profit by Customer", x = "Sales", y = "Profit")

Product Analysis by Region

superstore %>%
  group_by(order_id, product_name) %>%
  summarise(sum = sum(quantity)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sum)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() + 
    labs(title = "Count of Purchased Items by Quantity", x = "Quantity", y = "Count", fill = "")

plot_category_quantity = 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(category)%>%
  summarise(sum_quantity = sum(quantity))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = category, y = sum_quantity)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Quantity by Category", x = "Region", y = "Quantity")
plot_category_sales = 
superstore %>%
  group_by(category)%>%
  summarise(sum_sales = sum(sales))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = category, y = sum_sales )) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() + 
    labs(title = "Sales by Category", x = "Region", y = "Sales")
plot_category_profit = 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(category)%>%
  summarise(sum_profit = sum(profit))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = category, y = sum_profit)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Profit by Category", x = "Region", y = "Profit")
plot_category_profit_ratio = 
superstore %>%
  group_by(category)%>%
  summarise(profit_ratio = sum(profit)/sum(sales)*100)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = category, y = profit_ratio)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Profit Ratio by Category", x = "Region", y = "% of Profit Ratio")
grid.arrange(plot_category_quantity, plot_category_sales, plot_category_profit, plot_category_profit_ratio )

Customer Analysis by Region

plot_customer_count = 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(count = n_distinct(customer_id))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = region, y = count)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Customer Count by Region", x = "Region", y = "Customers")
plot_customer_quantity= 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(sum_of_sales= sum(quantity)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = region, y = sum_of_sales)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Quantity by Region", x = "Region", y = "Quantity")
plot_customer_sales= 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(sum_of_sales= round(sum(sales))) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = region, y = sum_of_sales)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Sales by Region", x = "Region", y = "Sales")
   
plot_sales_per_customer= 
  superstore %>%
  group_by( region) %>%
  summarise(sum = sum(sales)/n_distinct(customer_id)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = region, y = sum)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Sales Per Customer by Region", x = "Region", y = "Sales per Customer")
  
plot_profit = 
  superstore %>% 
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(sum_profit = sum(profit)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = region, y = sum_profit)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Profit by Region", x = "Region", y = "Profit")
plot_profit_ratio = 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(profit_ratio = round(sum(profit)/sum(sales)*100)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = region, y = profit_ratio)) +
    geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(title = "Profit Ratio", x = "Region", y = "% of Profit Ratio")
grid.arrange(plot_customer_count, plot_customer_quantity, plot_customer_sales, plot_sales_per_customer, plot_profit, plot_profit_ratio)

customer_ranking = 
  superstore %>%
  group_by(customer_id, customer_name) %>%
  summarise(sum_sales = sum(sales)) %>%
  arrange(desc(sum_sales)) %>%
  head(25)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(customer_name,sum_sales), y = sum_sales)) +
  geom_bar(alpha = 0.8, stat = 'identity', fill = "#1F77B4" ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Customer Ranking by Sales", x = "Customer Names", y = "Sales")
customer_ranking
